<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / Survey of UK Property (15): Slightly less than shipshape -
Vanessa Houlder finds Bristol changing tack after the recession / The
South-west
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RECESSION has left deep scars on Bristol and the south-west. The buoyant
economic conditions enjoyed by the region in the 1980s evaporated in the
1990s as its core industries, including defence and financial services,
suffered severe setbacks.
After years of worrying about the problems of success, such as labour
shortages and congestion, Bristol has changed tack. Increasingly, it is
concerned about re-establishing a vibrant economic base. 'We cannot be
complacent,' says Mr Andrew May, chairman of the planning and development
committee of Bristol City Council. 'We have to develop new sectors.'
Agents report an upturn in interest in the past six months, from occupiers
in sectors such as computers and financial services. However, nobody denies
that letting market is difficult. 'The market is still tough. Companies are
very cost conscious. It takes them a long time to make a move,' says Mr
Michael Finucane, of King Sturge, chartered surveyors.
Weak demand has taken a toll on office rents. Asking rents are down by about
a tenth from their peak; the decline is greater if tenants' incentives, such
as rent-free periods are taken into account. Renting second-hand space in
the centre costs Pounds 8-10 a sq ft a year, while new space commands about
Pounds 20 a sq ft.
The amount of empty office space in Bristol stands at about 1.7m sq ft,
equivalent to about 12 per cent of the total stock. That is below the
national average for city centre offices, which is estimated to be about 15
per cent.
The oversupply is particularly noticeable in small buildings of less than
2000 sq ft, which account for over 1m sq ft of the empty space. 'In recent
years, small self-contained buildings, typical of the Clifton and Queen
Square areas, have declined in popularity relative to open-plan
accommodation, which is perceived by occupiers as being more efficient,'
according to Chesterton, chartered surveyors.
The stock of vacant new buildings in Bristol, which account for about
500,000 sq ft of space, is relatively small compared with previous downturns
in the property cycle, such as the early 1980s.
This is, in large part, attributable to the council's past restraint when
granting planning permission. Recently, it has begun to take a less rigid
stance, as part of its efforts to bolster the city's occupier base.
Hitherto, however, the council's tough line with developers, coupled with
its concern about issues such as conservation, car restraint and
environmental issues, has provoked concern that the city was indifferent to
the needs of the property market and commercial occupiers.
A recent survey by APR for the Estates Gazette uncoveredwidespread criticism
by Bristol companies which considered that the motorist and commercial
occupier were badly catered for. Many said they would consider relocating to
an out-of-town centre, motivated by desire to escape the traffic and parking
problems and be nearer a motorway.
The popularity of the out-of-town market, which includes schemes such as
Arlington's Aztec West business park, is evident from its success in
securing lettings against competition from the city centre.
The out-of-town market accounted for 200,000 sq ft of the 380,000 sq ft of
space that was taken up in Bristol last year. The 200,000 sq ft of space
that was taken up in the first six months of 1993 was split evenly between
the town centre and the out-of-town centres.
Concern about the competition from out-of-town centres is not limited to the
office market. The city's retailers are soon to face competition from Cribbs
Causeway, a 650,000 sq ft regional shopping centre close to junction 17 of
the M5. The scheme, which is being developed by J T Baylis and the
Prudential, is due to start construction next year.
In general, however, development in Bristol is at low ebb. Although 1.85m sq
ft of offices have planning permission, most schemes are likely to remain on
the drawing board for some time. An exception is the second phase of the
95,000 sq ft Trinity Quay scheme being developed by the Church
Commissioners, which was pre-sold to the National Westminster Bank for
Pounds 40m last year.
Few schemes are likely to start without securing a tenant in advance.
According to Chesterton, the schemes that are most likely to begin
construction include Temple Meads, where the Bristol Development Corporation
has planning permission for up to 250,000 sq ft; Bond Street, where National
Provident has planning permission for up to 110,000 sq ft of new offices;
Thomas Paty House, where there is planning permission for 65,000 sq ft of
offices; and Newfoundland Street, where Wyndham Investments is planning
80,000 sq ft of offices.
The Bristol Development Corporation, the regeneration body, has announced
several other proposed developments, including a Pounds 20m office scheme by
Dysart Development and a Pounds 50m retail and leisure complex by Wilson
Connolly at Avon Meads, next to the new spine road it is building to link
the M32 in the north to the A4 Bath Road in the south.
Hanson, the conglomerate, has also proposed a large retail and leisure
scheme on a former Wills tobacco factory in South Bristol.
In the warehouse sector, there is more evidence to support an early
resumption of development activity. A distribution warehouse scheme at St
Philips Central, which is being promoted by Bristol &amp; England Properties,
has already secured lettings for about three-quarters of its space.
The investment market is also making slow progress in Bristol and the
south-west. Although the institutions have the capacity to make investments,
there is a distinct shortage of the type of buildings - with long leases and
financially secure tenants - that they find attractive.
A strong pick-up in the letting market will eventually feed through into new
investment opportunities. On the current showing, however, that is still
some way off.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
