<PROFILE>_AN-DKSDHAIJFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931119
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / Survey of UK Property (14): Manchester's paradox encourages
relocation - Ian Hamilton Fazey examines the regional capital's imbalance
between supply and demand / The North-west
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SURPRISING frisson of anxiety is rippling through north-west England's
property community, particularly in Greater Manchester. Some specialists are
beginning to talk about shortages - in spite of more than 1m square feet of
overhanging, unlet new office space from the 1980s.
This paradox arises because the market is not homogeneous. Pockets of
increasing demand do not coincide with pockets of oversupply. Demand is
rising in the city centre; the area around Manchester Airport continues to
be attractive, because of the airport's growth; and Chester remains one of
the most pleasant parts of England to live and work.
All three pockets are short of good, new, high quality space. The region's
most concentrated bulk of this, however, is in the old Manchester Ship Canal
docklands at Salford Quays and Trafford Park, where two expiring enterprise
zones encouraged a spate of rapid building in the late 1980s. About 1m sq ft
of modern space can be had at relatively soft rents.
Some of the mismatch between supply and demand is encouraging modest
relocation within the region, with parts of Cheshire hoping to benefit, and
some take-up at Salford Quays. But it seems unlikely to knock on much into
Merseyside, which is still trying to put right its promotional problems and
where demand is relatively poor and supply modest anyway.
The effect is likely to be most obvious in the next 18 months on rents in
Manchester's city centre. This prime area sets the region's rental standard
 -a headline range between Pounds 20 and Pounds 23 a sq ft - with demand
driven by the city's financial and professional services sector, which grew
steadily throughout the 1980s, making Manchester Britain's foremost banking
centre outside London.
This is part of an ever more obvious regional trend echoed elsewhere in
Europe. Self-standing regional financial centres are developing to service
regional economies, as these local markets become too small to offer
economies of scale to national centres.
This intrinsic source of demand is now being augmented as a result of the
north-west's suffering less than elsewhere in the recession and showing
signs of recovering faster. The region's rate of economic growth more than
doubled to 3.2 per cent a year in 1986-90 - about the national average - but
shrunk by only 1.7 per cent in 1991.
By contrast, UK gross domestic product declined by 2.4 per cent in 1991,
with regions like the West Midlands (3.0 per cent), the East Midlands (1.8
per cent) and East Anglia (2.9 per cent) suffering much more than the
north-west - their downturn being accentuated further by growth rates of 4
per cent or more in the 1980s.
But while these last three regional economies continued to shrink last year,
north-west England's stood still at zero growth. In other words, it turned
earlier. The net impact of the north-west's suffering a shallower recession
than the Midlands and south is a stirring of demand now.
As Simon Reynolds, partner in charge of business space at the Manchester
office of Grimley JR Eve, the chartered surveyors, puts it: 'Third-quarter
inquiries were 23 per cent up on the second quarter and well ahead of last
year. Our problem is we have no tower cranes. Top-quality property at the
top end of the market is a rarity. We have decreasing supply and rising
demand.'
What top-quality space there is in Manchester city centre is filling and
changing hands. Some had its end user lined up from the outset, as with the
new Manchester headquarters of KPMG Peat Marwick, the accountant. Trinity
Court, developed by Barlows, the Chester property company, has already
attracted Hammond Suddards, the Leeds law firm now expanding in Manchester,
and NM Rothschild, the merchant bank.
Although top-of-the-range headline rents are said to be holding, Mr Reynolds
points out: 'True market rents are realistically around Pounds 14 or Pounds
15, because of the deals that are being done.'
Deals might include several months of rental holidays - usually enough to
pay for fitting out and furnishings - and the developer paying for a
relocater's old leases for a limited period, or until they can be assigned.
The hope is that markets will pick up in time to save both parties
embarrassment when the period runs out.
As the economy improves, most property professionals expect no growth in
headline rents, but rather an improvement in effective rents as deals
tighten up. However, what is happening now is adding to potentially
difficult problem.
Mr Reynolds says: 'The dark side of the market is second-hand space. The
real millstone is 1.33m sq ft of it in Manchester. This will rise to 1.75m
sq ft in about two years' time. The deals that are being done now to get big
tenants to move are leaving behind a potential glut of second-hand space
that will be increasingly difficult to shift.
'The hope is that the lack of new space will mean good second-hand space
will start to go, but it takes four to five years to let buildings dating
from the 1960s and 1970s. You have to thoroughly refurbish them to have any
chance.'
With no shortage of potential foreign investors, the hope is more tower
cranes will start to appear soon as developers replace old offices, a
process that usually takes a couple of years per building. In the meantime,
The Quays - a couple of miles from Manchester city centre - offer the
north-west's only concentration of good space.
The three schemes there - the Anchorage, Harbour City and Exchange Quay -
were developed respectively by Amec, Manchester Ship Canal Company, now
absorbed into Peel Holdings, and the Charter Group, which went down in the
recession. About 230,000 sq ft should be let by Christmas - 50,000 sq ft was
let in the summer, 100,000 sq ft is in legal process and 80,000 sq ft went
last year.
This leaves about 945,000 sq ft to go, but at around Pounds 15 a sq ft with
incentives thrown in as well, it offers good value, given its quality,
waterside location and links to the motorway system and the airport. Mr
Reynolds says the Quays needs one of its three schemes to be fully let and
another about 60 per cent full for rents to start hardening.
Meanwhile, confidence is rising among retailers. Peel last month cleared the
final legal hurdle in the way of the Trafford Centre, a 300-acre regional
shopping centre on the banks of the ship canal near the convergence of five
motorways. About 7m people will be within an hour's drive. It should open in
1997.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6552 Subdividers and Developers, Ex Cemeteries.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
