<DOCNO>FT934-7355</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DKSDHAIIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931119
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / Survey of UK Property (11): European fruit in the heart of
England - Birmingham is near the top of investors' shopping lists / The
Midlands
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANNE STEADMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MIDLANDS property market was far from immune to the recession. But it
was not hit by the same degree of overbuilding - and rental spiral followed
by free fall - as the south.
Some Midlands cities, with the benefit of European cash, began initiatives
during the recession, which are now bearing fruit.
Birmingham city council, for example, has made significant improvements.
Pedestrian areas have been opened, linking the traditional city core area
with the west end, where the National Convention Centre - again built with
the help of European grants - is located. The canal network is being
rejuvenated as a feature.
Birmingham (along with Manchester and Leeds) now features strongly near the
top of property investors' shopping lists, according to Ed Luker of Richard
Ellis.
There is an evident shortage of prime new office space in the city centre.
So much so, says Geoff Thomas, of DTZ Debenham Thorpe, that there is 'every
indication of an imminent new phase of speculative development'.
One of the most high-profile current developments is Temple Court, in Bull
Street, a major refurbishment of the former Lewis's department store by
Richardson Barberry Properties.
Coopers &amp; Lybrand has taken 100,000 sq ft on a pre-let at over Pounds 20 a
sq ft, while the Lord Chancellor's department has bought a long lease on a
further 130,000 sq ft. There is also a retail element. Temple Court has now
been bought by John Ritblat's British Land for Pounds 32m - a price which
reflects an estimated yield in respect of the offices of around 8.5 per
cent, according to Simon Robinson, of Richard Ellis, Birmingham.
Altogether, development completions over the past 18 months have totalled
651,000 sq ft (net), estimates surveyor Chestertons. Most were built
speculatively, and include:
Balfour Beatty/Church Commissioners' 136,000 sq ft 55 Colmore Row, which was
pre-let to solicitor Wragge &amp; Co at Pounds 23.50 a sq ft; the Church
Commissioners' Colmore Gate, 2-8 Colmore Row, where there have been lettings
to Royal Insurance (75,000 sq ft) and Touche Ross (42,000 sq ft) and the
remaining 30,000 sq ft is under offer; and the Chateau in Victoria Square,
taken by TSB as its new headquarters. TSB has subsequently bought the
152,000 sq ft building.
There is growing pressure on investment yields, partly because of
Birmingham's under-supplied status, and partly because of conditions in the
current investment market itself - large amounts of money available and
relatively few properties on offer. Mr Robinson reckons that the next big
Birmingham office transaction will be struck at 'well below 8 per cent'.
The new convention centre, along with the council's improvement of access
and rejuvenation, have led to a flurry of activity in the surrounding West
End area. One of several developments is Helmwell's 100,000 sq ft canalside
Tindal Bridge office project, where one third has already been let to
Property Holdings and the Vehicle Registration office.
The strategic location of Birmingham and other Midlands areas makes them
logical choices for distribution facilities. Severn Trent Property's 90-acre
Midpoint Park, on the north-east edge of Birmingham, is home to Cadbury's
new 400,000 sq ft warehouse. And garden equipment manufacturer Hozelock has
agreed terms for a 175,000 sq ft facility, which will open in autumn next
year.
In Coventry there is also a new initiative to revitalise the city centre.
The council is seeking to raise Pounds 22m this year, mainly by the sale of
property assets - land and leasehold interests with marriage value.
With additional cash from Europe and the private sector, it will aim to
undertake joint ventures with private sector companies, says David Holt, of
Richard Ellis. Among the key areas identified is the Lower Precinct, part of
the main shopping centre, where there are hopes of a new department store.
Out-of-town business parks around Coventry have enjoyed considerable
success. The City of Coventry's Westwood Business Park is almost complete,
now that PowerGen has taken a 126,000 sq ft headquarters. P&amp;O Properties'
110-acre Middlemarch park houses companies that include Digital Microwave,
Peugot Talbot and Tangram Computers. And there is now only one building, the
36,000 sq ft Stone Court left available, according to Mr Holt. A new phase
will be launched next year.
In Nottingham, the office market is extremely tight, with no new or
refurbished space over 10,000 sq ft available. The main reason is the delay
caused by the design competition for the new Inland Revenue headquarters.
This has led to the Revenue taking some 115,000 sq ft of offices in various
buildings on three- to 15-year leases, mopping up most of the excess offices
in the city. Most of the government's short lettings were concluded at
around Pounds 10 a sq ft. With at least five major unfilled requirements in
the market - mostly other government departments looking to relocate to more
modern offices - pre-lets are being negotiated at about Pounds 12 a sq ft.
The new 409,000 sq ft Inland Revenue building is now going up in Castle
Meadow with completion scheduled for 1994-95. Chesterton points out that the
market could well be flooded with second-hand space over the next few years
 -as the Revenue comes out of its temporary offices and leases on many 1960s
office developments fall in and the tenants move out. Much of the poorer
stock is likely to be unlettable.
Further south, Milton Keynes has suffered the same problems as locations
such as Watford - rocketing rents and overbuilding in the spill over from
the London market. Rents at the peak were as high as Pounds 17 to Pounds 18
a sq ft. Now, with around 600,000 sq ft of empty space - out of a total
stock in the central area of 1.3m sq ft - latest lettings have achieved
Pounds 8 a sq ft plus 'small giveaways', according to Roger Saper, of Jones
Lang Wootton. Some have been as low as Pounds 5 a sq ft. The largest
available building is Norwich Union's' 143,000 sq ft Witan Gate House,
which, it is understood, was considered and rejected by both BT and Nissan.
Quoting rent is Pounds 15 a sq ft.
During the boom of the 1980s, take-up of office space was up to 300,000 a
year. Agents are looking at several years before the vacant space
overhanging the market is absorbed. Until most of it is, the Milton Keynes
office market is effectively stalled.
Swindon's office market has been spared the worst of the development spree
which plagued most of the M4 corridor. But, though there is a limited amount
of good, new space, there is a massive amount of second-hand accommodation,
says Alistair Elliot, of surveyor Knight Frank &amp; Rutley. Quoting rents for
second-hand space ranges from Pounds 6 to Pounds 12 a sq ft.
However, at St Martins' successful Windmill Hill business park, a new
305,000 sq ft phase is under construction. Rents achieved at Windmill Hill
so far are Pounds 15 a sq ft.
</TEXT>
