<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / Survey of UK Property (12): Southampton sails ahead - But
Portsmouth has been hit by cuts in the Royal Navy and the defence industry /
The South
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANNE STEADMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE OPENING of the controversial M3 link through Twyford Down, scheduled for
the end of next year, will integrate the south coast towns with the national
motorway network.
Principal beneficiary is likely to be Southampton, possibly at the expense
of Basingstoke and Winchester to the north. Southampton exhibits as clear a
case as any of the two-tier office market present in most UK cities. There
is a limited supply of high specification new space which is letting at up
to Pounds 18.50 a sq ft, compared with Pounds 14 two years ago. There is
also plenty of empty space in second-hand buildings, of which some 250,000
sq ft is within 1960s and 1970s tower blocks.
Most of this older accommodation is poorly specified, without
air-conditioning or acceptable on-site parking provision. Rents are as low
as Pounds 5 a sq ft, rising to Pounds 13 for good refurbishments.
The only two new buildings in the city centre are the 36,500 sq ft Skandia
House, in Portland Place, where Eagle Star has recently taken 22,000 sq ft
at a rent believed to be in the region of Pounds 18 a sq ft, and
Timberlaine's 16,250 sq ft Mountbatten House in Grosvenor Square.
A further two new office buildings are under construction, both in
Commercial Road. Scottish Amicable is putting up 65,000 sq ft for completion
at the end of this year, and Timberlaine has made a start on 40,000 sq ft to
be known as Thorneycroft House.
A number of proposals are in the pipeline. But most are unlikely to go ahead
without pre-lets in place, according to Andrew Wood, of Chestertons.
Prospective developments include: Brunswick Gate, Brunswick Place, where
Bryant Developments has planning permission for 46,000 sq ft of offices;
Queens Quay, where Associated British Ports has a 28-acre site with consent
for up to 375,000 sq ft of offices; the Pirelli site, on Western Esplanade,
where the city council and Pirelli have outline consent for a mixed
development.
Martin Tice, of surveyor Vail Williams, considers, however, that the gradual
increase in demand, apparent since the beginning of this year, could lead
developers and funds to take another look at opportunities dismissed through
lack of confidence no more than 18 months ago.
Several out-of-town sites could also provide new office space. Arlington has
consent for a further 500,000 sq ft on its Solent Business Park at junction
9 on the M27; and at junction 7 there is potential for up to 200,000 sq ft
at the Botleigh Grange office campus.
London &amp; Edinburgh Trust has been granted planning for up to 1.5m sq ft of
business space on its site at junction 5 - at Eastleigh Airport, which is
being upgraded regularly and now offers a comprehensive European service.
Neighbouring Portsmouth has been hard hit by cutbacks in the Royal Navy, the
defence industry and problems at IBM and other major computer companies. And
it looks set for further suffering with more local jobs under threat.
However, while the Isle of Wight has successfully achieved Assisted Area
status, Portsmouth's bid was turned down.
There has been a dearth of new office building in the city over the past few
years, notes Mr Tice. However, two recent lettings have given confidence to
a sluggish office market. Insurance broker Rossborough UK has taken 9,614 sq
ft on two floors at the Swedish Slaget's (part of the Lundberg Group) 68,500
sq ft, 10-storey Baltic House on the northern fringe of the city centre. It
is Portsmouth's only air-conditioned office building.
The other significant letting is to the department for the environment,
which has taken the 13,666 sq ft Wynnstay House office building in Cosham.
The building will be occupied as the Cosham job centre and offices, on a
20-year lease with a 15-year break clause.
There has been a slow but steady revival in industrial demand in the
Portsmouth area this year, after three years of decline. The market is still
unsettled, however.
Little new industrial/warehouse space has been built around Portsmouth over
the past four years. Vail Williams estimates that current supply - excluding
Gosport, Fareham, Havant and Waterlooville - is around 635,000 sq ft; with
only 10 per cent in new buildings. So here, too, there is a marked two-tier
market, and occupiers looking for good modern space face limited options. Of
these, one is Blueprint Portsmouth, a 34-acre development by British Gas
Properties on the eastern outskirts of the city. Two recent lettings of
8,600 sq ft and 13,150 sq ft have achieved rents rising to Pounds 6 a sq ft.
Nearby, close to the junction of the A27 and Eastern Road, John Menzies has
taken a pre-let of a new 17,150 sq ft warehouse and office building at
Pounds 6.26 a sq ft.
At the site of the former airport, Percy Bilton has 10 acres of land
available for pre-lettings at its Bilton Business Park and Gatcombe House
Properties, and Portsmouth city council is soon to make a start on an
eight-acre site at North Harbour.
On a larger scale, Stand Harbour Securities, a joint venture between
Portsmouth-based Warings Group and businessman Bob Merrick, is busy with a
143,225 sq ft business park at the environmentally sensitive Cams Hall
estate close to junction 11 on the M27 at Fareham. Centrepiece of the park
will be the restored listed hall itself, built in 1620 by Hampshire high
sheriff Emmanuel Badd and rebuilt in 1767.
As part of the agreement with the council, the estate's parkland and
surrounding woods will be restored and there will be an extension to the
coastal footpath around the whole Cams Hall Peninsula, completing the
missing link from Fareham to Porchester. There are also two new 18-hole golf
courses.
Bournemouth has, over the years, attracted finance companies and insurance
companies, including Abbey Life, Zurich Assurance and Lloyds Bowmaker. There
has been very little speculative development. The one exception is Slough
Estates' Wessex Fields, which offers two buildings, one air-conditioned of
some 50,000 sq ft and the other 20,000 sq ft. Completed two years ago and
marketed at Pounds 17 and Pounds 15 a sq ft respectively, both are still
vacant except for part of one floor in the smaller building. Asking rent is
now down to Pounds 13.
</TEXT>
