<PROFILE>_AN-DKSDHAIFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931119
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / Survey of UK Property (9): The motorway effect arrives late
in the north - The home counties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANNE STEADMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE OPENING of the M40 extension, providing a fast link from London to
Birmingham, was expected to have an impact on the surrounding areas.
But its timing, coinciding with the Gulf war and the worst of the recession,
meant that only recently have the anticipated effects begun to be seen,
observes James Kennedy-Cooke, of DTZ Debenham Thorpe.
The new Charwell Valley services at junction 10, to open next summer, should
add impetus to the warehouse market. And at nearby junction 11, AMEC and
Abbey Life have just completed the 103,000 sq ft MXL centre, at Banbury -
the M40's only high-quality distribution centre.
Oxford city centre has seen a gradual revival in demand over the past six
months, says Scott Harkness, of surveyor Adkin Commercial. He estimates
that, during this time, 45,000 sq ft of good modern space has been let.
Adding smaller developments and second-hand space to that would take the
total to between 80,000 and 109,000 sq ft.
In common with many other locations, central Oxford has seen virtually no
speculative developments completed in the past three years. And though there
is still space available, it is slowly being taken up.
In Cambridge, activity revolves around research-based and technology
industries. Some companies are now looking at further expansion. There is,
says John Tweddle, of surveyor Bidwells, a strong resurgence of interest in
this sector, with a spate of lettings at the Cambridge Science Park and
several proposals to add to or create new premises. In addition, developer
Bride Hall, says Andrew Lawrence, of surveyor Connells Commercial, is busy
with a new phase at the science park, where rents range from around Pounds
10 to Pounds 12 a sq ft - down from their peak of Pounds 14 to Pounds 15.
It is a different picture in the city centre, where rents peaked at around
Pounds 23 a sq ft but have now halved. Available space stands at between
600,000 sq ft and 700,000 sq ft, Mr Lawrence estimates. However, that
compares with some 1m sq ft two years ago.
At Ipswich, Kim Watson-Powell, of Bidwells, sees signs of a revival of
interest, mainly from professional firms.  However, although there is a
great deal of talk, it has yet to be translated into actual transactions.
Ipswich suffers from a shortage of good-quality office space and an almost
total absence of 'institutional' quality buildings.
At Chelmsford, 1992 is reckoned to have been the low point in the office
market. Only 30,000 sq ft was taken up. This year, that figure should at
least double, particularly if Tarmac Brookglade's 36,000 sq ft County House,
currently under offer, is duly signed up, says Nicholas Jones, of Nelson
Bakewell, who adds that there will then be no new offices available in lot
sizes of over 10,000 sq ft.
Basildon is not an established office centre, and activity is centred on
out-of-town space. Recent lettings include 43,000 sq ft by Ford Motor
Company at Trafalgar House's Southfields Business Park, where there is now
only around 3,500 sq ft still available, according to Stuart Mole, of
surveyor Glenny. Demand has picked up, although it is still inconsistent, he
adds.
South Bedfordshire towns, including Luton and Bedford, are suffering from an
over-supply of new space. The area has been affected by cuts at General
Motors over the past 10 years, and unemployment is high.
There has been little speculative development since Capability Green in the
mid-1980s, says Roger Saper, of Jones Lang Wootton. The 90-acre business
park, where 350,000 sq ft has been built, now houses tenants that include
Whitbread, Barclays, Nabisco and Siemens.
There is 33 acres for development at the park, which boasts as high a
standard as any in the UK. Jones Lang Wootton are now marketing the entire
development on behalf of the estate of NH Phillips, the original developer.
There has been some interest in buildings at the 35-acre Houghton Hall Park,
at Houghton Regis. The striking Herculean building offers a total of 60,000
sq ft in three wings, and has been developed by Danish consortium
Laserglide.
Glaxo, which is building a new research campus on a 75-acre site in Gunnels
Wood, dominates the current market in Stevenage. The pharmaceutical giant
already has a further 25-acre site for expansion. But it is also understood
to be on the look-out for more sites in the Gunnels Wood area.
The largest office letting in Stevenage in the past 18 months was in Gunnels
Wood, where Penta Technologies took the 16,000 sq ft Chadwell House at
Universities Superannuation Scheme's business and industrial park. On a
10-year lease, rent rises to Pounds 200,000 in the fifth year.
In the town centre, one of the largest office buildings available is Cramond
Lelliot's 68,250 sq ft Kings Court, close to the railway station. Asking
rent is Pounds 17.50 a sq ft. Markheath's King's Court, a 22-acre site again
close to the station, has infrastructure in place for 600,000 sq ft of
offices. It is one of six sites identified by the Hertfordshire Development
Organisation's marketing plan as of strategic significance in attracting
inward investment from overseas.
The Reading office market received a boost early this year with news of the
sale of Kumagai Gumi/Ranelagh Developments' 121 Kings Road for some Pounds
45m, to OIL Property Investment, the property investment arm of the German
Hypo Bank. This sale, at a yield of just over 9.3 per cent, was one of the
first of a growing number of provincial office investments made by overseas
investors. Tarmac's 29,000 sq ft Adelphi House, let to the DSS, is also said
to be attracting interest at yields of 7-7.5 per cent.
The only new building in central Reading due for completion within the next
two years, says Mr Head, will be CIN's 51,000 sq ft Phoenix House adjoining
the station. However, Tim Warboys, of Jones Lang Wootton, says that the firm
has received a conditional offer for the post office site, again next to the
station, subject to planning consent for 50,000 sq ft of offices and the
refurbishment of the original post office.
Competition from out of town comes from Arlington's 720,000 sq ft business
park at Theale, where KPMG Peat Marwick has signed up a 30,000 sq ft
pre-let. Arlington is quoting rents of Pounds 24.50 a sq ft - and this
figure looks likely to be repeated for new space in the town centre.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
