<PROFILE>_AN-DKSDHAIDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931119
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / Survey of UK Property (8): The industry looks west - Two
recent surveys offer grounds for optimism / The M25
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LAWSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AROUND THE fringes of London is a tarmac tidemark left by the city's Big
Bang. Hundreds of empty buildings litter the M25 landscape.
'It epitomises everything that went wrong during the boom,' says Stephen
Mallen, head of research at Knight Frank &amp; Rutley. 'Banks were throwing
money at developers, who indulged in some of the worst excesses of
speculation.'
More than half the 14m sq ft of available office space around the motorway
corridor is concentrated in a short stretch between the M4 and the A1(M),
according to Mr Mallen. In some bloated centres, a fifth of space stands
empty, and rent levels have halved since the boom. Many obsolete older
buildings may never see another tenant, as they cannot compete with a
plethora of new ones.
Go east of Potters Bar or the A23, however, and such excesses disappear. Big
office schemes are rare, because the money that did flow into the eastern
zone went into its traditional strengths - distribution and retailing. It is
no coincidence that Costco, the US warehouse club, which recently overcame
blocking moves by Britain's biggest retailers, has chosen to build its first
UK outlet next to the Lakeside Shopping Centre at Thurrock, where the M25
crosses the Thames. It might, therefore, seem logical to look at this
under-developed area for any recovery. The government favours development
along the East Thames corridor, and the Channel link will help depressed
areas of south Essex and north Kent.
Site preparation is already going on among big landowners like Blue Circle,
but any general uplift seems unlikely to take off for several years, because
of political prevarications. The Channel link is likely to be delayed yet
again by spending limits in the Budget. 'And the government has yet to put
its money where its mouth is over the East Thames Corridor,' says Mr Mallen.
So the industry is looking westward for more immediate opportunities, and
two studies provide evidence that this is not a forlorn hope. Tenants
absorbed 3.7m sq ft of space in buildings greater than 5,000 sq ft in the
first nine months of this year - 12 per cent more than that in the whole of
1992, according to a Richard Ellis survey.
KFR, which sets a higher threshold of 10,000 sq ft for the buildings it
monitors, comes to similar conclusions. The overall vacancy rate dropped to
just over 13.5 per cent in the three months to September, the largest drop
since it began quarterly reports 18 months ago. 'The market has definitely
turned since the beginning of this year,' says Mr Mallen.
Even more welcome to banks nursing burned fingers is the fact that the new
space they funded is in greatest demand, accounting for 75 per cent of
deals. Much of the property is going to local companies, which do not have
the same problems getting rid of existing space as in central London. They
are taking the chance to grab high-quality buildings at rents ranging from
Pounds 15 to Pounds 20 a sq ft, compared with as much as Pounds 30 in the
boom. Industry and business services accounted for more than half this
year's take-up, with computing companies and the public sector absorbing
around 15 per cent each, says Richard Ellis.
Big names are also back in the market. Important deals in the last few
months have included the 96,000 sq ft Lansdowne Building in Croydon, taken
by Tarmac; Eastern Gate, Bracknell, (63.500 sq ft) let to Mortgage Services;
and Athena Court, Hounslow (54,000 sq ft) to BSkyB.
Chris Hiatt, of Jones Lang Wootton, which has carried out a detailed
analysis of the office market west of London, points out that, while the
area as a whole has up to five years' supply available, some centres are
much closer to equilibrium. Vacancy rates in new buildings have fallen below
5 per cent in centres like Windsor, Maidenhead, Staines, Croydon and Woking.
Others, such as Guildford, Redhill and High Wycombe, are below the
psychologically important 10 per cent level.
JLW forecasts stronger economic recovery in the region than in the rest of
the UK, pushing tenant demand back to its long-term average, just at a time
when minimal new space is coming on to the market.
Shortages of high-quality buildings are already emerging, leading to the
first inquiries in nearly three years from developers interested in
speculative building, says Tony Fisher, of Chesterton. He picks out AXA
Equity and Law, which spent Pounds 8.3m to take over Maidenhead Business
Park to create up to 300,000 sq ft. 'This trend will continue on the
assumption of demand outweighing supply, and land values being offered at
today's prices, although whether this can be sustained for much longer
remains to be seen.'
Few expect a return to the lemming-like rush of the boom years, when
planning changes enabled every industrial estate to magically transform
overnight into an office park. Andrew Nesbitt, AXA property director, does
not intend starting development for at least a year, unless he can net one
of several major names currently in the market for space.
But with JLW forecasting a return to rental growth from the end of next
year, more investors will be scouting around the this section of the M25 in
the near future. At the opposite extreme, others will be looking for
industrial opportunities out in the eastern sector, where rents of Pounds 7
a sq ft and more now match former boom centres like Heathrow, but land is
far cheaper and planning rules less restrictive.
</TEXT>
<XX>
