<PROFILE>_AN-DKSDHAICFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931119
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / Survey of UK Property (6): Diagnoses in conflict - A
prominent consultant sees gloom. A prominent park developer disagrees
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LAWSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TAKE-UP ON business parks has collapsed by 75 per cent since the the late
1980s, says property consultant DTZ Debenham Thorpe.
Its study of parks, published earlier this year, shows that investment deals
formed less than 1 per cent of the property market last year, compared with
12 per cent in 1990; and that development is running at a mere third of peak
levels.
As head of Arlington Securities, Britain's biggest park developer, Patrick
Deigman might be expected to be discouraged. However, his company has nearly
a dozen projects under way, with more than 5.5m sq ft still to be built.
Beyond these sit more than 20m sq ft in the pipeline. Even so, the company
set alarm bells ringing around the market recently by laying off staff.
But the statistics are incorrect, insists Mr Deigman. There had never been a
tidal wave of potential development. A crowd of no-hopers had jumped on the
bandwagon during the boom.
The lay-offs were not a sign of falling business, but part of an internal
reorganisation under which property investments were transferred to the
British Aerospace parent company, he says. 'We should clock up more than 1m
sq ft this year,' says Mr Deigman. Institutions are also falling over
themselves to diversify out of city centre holdings, he adds, forecasting
yields under 7.5 per cent by the end of the year.
'We get a letting every month or two, and intend to restart development next
year,' says Philip Wakeling, who looks after Colchester Business Park for
GRE. But rents are down from 14 to 10 a sq ft, and nothing will be built
without a pre-let.
DTZ Debenham Thorpe says that business parks have fallen into an even bigger
black hole than the notorious City of London office market since 1988. Yet
Paul Lunn, of Applied Property Research, which provided the basic
statistics, is busy stripping out developments which have no chance of going
ahead or boast dubious claims to business park status. This could cut supply
by 40 per cent. Even that figure will be debatable, however, as no one can
agree on how to define a business park.
Some analysts refuse to acknowledge any scheme that includes manufacturing
or warehouses, which is ironic, considering that a new generation of parks
now on the drawing board will contain the whole spectrum of business
activity - and maybe even housing. Others set a minimum of 100 acres for the
'true' park, ignoring the fact that some of the most successful schemes over
the last decade are much smaller.
Even the much-reduced total still leaves what appears to be a vast
over-capacity, however. Business parks flourished in the 1980s, because
tenants were either squeezed out of town centres by soaring rents or buoyant
enough to take swish new premises on greenfield locations. Today, neither of
these pressures seems to apply.
Wrong again, says Mr Deigman. Firstly, recession makes businesses look hard
at costs, and discover that property makes up little more than 5 per cent of
bills. People are the big expense, and moving them to a more efficient
environment can raise productivity. He quotes KPMG, which has just decided
to centralise its Oxford and Reading offices in 30,000 sq ft at Theale, near
Reading. The rent is likely to be around Pounds 24 a sq ft, compared with
town-centre level of Pounds 15.
This kind of letting will be vital in future, says DTZ. Business parks have
to grab a larger slice of total demand or widen their appeal to include
town-centre tenants. Some are much better placed than others to do this.
'Business parks reflect the health of their local region,' says John
Heawood, of DTZ. 'This is inevitable, as 80 per cent of tenants move no more
than 20 miles.'
Trafalgar House, for instance, has picked up two of the largest deals ever
seen on a business park through local moves. At Brooklands, in Weybridge,
Surrey, both Sony and Procter &amp; Gamble are building huge new headquarters
only a few miles from their old homes. Both also bought freehold sites to
create bespoke buildings, which is now about the only activity taking place
in the sector, as developers have stopped speculative building.
Even the best locations will fail unless they can offer accessibility and
amenity, however. Tenants surveyed by Weatherall Green &amp; Smith gave road
links and parking as main reasons for selecting accommodation - far above
air conditioning or landscaping.
</TEXT>
