<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / Survey of UK Property (4): High streets see most development
 -The emphasis is on in-fill sites, because, although there is unlet
property in most towns, much is unsuitable / The retail market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RETAIL market, which led the way into the property recession, looks set
to lead the way out.
Having lost nearly a quarter of its value in the four years to May 1993,
retail property values have begun to recover. Investment yields have
declined sharply in many cases, while rental values have mostly stopped
falling. Even the property development market is showing the first signs of
a revival.
But many parts of the market are still far from buoyant. Rents on older
property in secondary locations are still declining in many parts of the
country; empty and boarded-up shops dominate many high streets and shopping
centres.
So far, there is little sign of rental growth. The improved confidence on
the part of landlords is chiefly a result of the reduced concessions they
are now forced to offer. The average incentive offered to a new tenant has
reduced from the equivalent of two years rent free to just nine months in
the past two years, according to Erdman Lewis.
The decline in the retail sector has been longer, but shallower, than other
parts of the market. From the high point to the low point of the market, the
fall in retail rents was 17 per cent, compared with 46 per cent for offices
and 23 per cent for industrial.
In the view of Healey &amp; Baker, rental growth is likely to resume in 1994 for
prime retail space, before reaching a plateau in the second half of the
decade as the growth in retail sales slows. As the market recovers, it
expects there will be short, sharp increases as centres realign to higher
demand, rather than a sustained upwards trend.
The uncertainties governing rental prospects extend beyond the outlook for
consumer spending. Much depends on the development cycle; the success of the
new wave of discount stores could also have a marked impact on the high
street.
Development activity is currently at low ebb, but the improvement in the
market may spur some developers to begin construction before planning
permissions obtained in the late eighties expire.
The main focus of development activity is in-fill sites in the high street.
Even though there is an ample supply of unlet properties in most towns, some
of this is deemed unsuitable because it is over-rented, poorly configured,
too dilapidated or in a poor location.
Outside town centres, development activity is currently subdued. Just 2.54m
sq ft of shopping centre floorspace is currently under construction, less
than 15 per cent of the 18.9m sq ft recorded at the peak of the 1980s
development boom.
The prospects of large out-of-town shopping centres winning planning
permission in the future have been much reduced as a result of a hardening
of the government's planning policies. Last year the Department of the
Environment issued a new policy guidance note, known as PPG6, which
emphasised the need to revitalise town centres, rather than promote large
out-of-town stores.
The prospects for construction in shopping centres that already have
planning permission is mixed. Cheshire Oaks, the planned shopping centre
outside Chester, suffered a setback in September when Boots pulled out as
the joint developer. In Bristol, however, the Cribbs Causeway shopping
centre is considered viable and is due to begin construction next Spring.
The viability of new development depends on consumer confidence and the
take-up of developments undertaken at the end of the 1980s. Conditions vary
considerably around the country and in different sectors of the retail
market.
Central and suburban London remain among the worst-performing areas in the
country, despite an upturn in interest from small multiple and independent
retailers.
Away from London, most shopping areas in the south-east have been stable in
the first half of 1993, according to Healey &amp; Baker, chartered surveyors.
In the same period in the Midlands, south-west and Wales, rents were fairly
stable; in East Anglia, feeble consumer demand resulted in a 3.1 per cent
decline in rents in the first half of the year; in the north of England they
fell declined slightly.
Scotland and Northern Ireland have seen a good recovery in the past six
months, with positive rental growth of 1.3 per cent and 2.3 per cent
respectively.
Retail warehouses have been the best performing part of the property market.
According to Erdman Lewis, chartered surveyors, total returns on an
annualised basis at June were 31.2 per cent for retail warehouses, compared
with 7.7 per cent for shops.
The foodstore market has also performed strongly, although the low level of
lettings makes its performance more difficult to assess. Demand is strong
for sites in the best locations, as a result of the expansion programmes of
the large store groups such as Sainsbury, Tesco and Safeway.
It remains to be seen how far their future is affected by the arrival of
discount stores. In particular, the large store groups are concerned about
the advance of warehouse clubs like CostCo, the US-style stores which
specialise in bulk sales in out-of-town locations.
The increasing emphasis on discounting is one factor that may hold back
profitability and growth in parts of the retail business. However, given the
constraints on new development and the improving prospects for consumer
spending, the coming year is likely to see a restoration of rental growth.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6552 Subdividers and Developers, Ex Cemeteries.
    P154  Nonresidential Building Construction.
</IN>
