<PROFILE>_AN-DKSDHAH9FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931119
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / Survey of UK Property (3): London leads the revival - The
upturn in demand, most visible in the capital, has been led by overseas
investors, particularly from Germany / The office market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE OFFICE market, long the sickest sector of the commercial property
industry, is beginning to stage a recovery.
The value of well-let properties has increased, as a marked decline in
investment yields - the ratio of income to capital - has compensated for a
continuing decline in rental values.
High-yielding office buildings, with financially secure tenants and long
leases, have become increasingly attractive to investors, as bond yields
have declined. This upturn in investment demand has been noted throughout
the UK, as investors' traditional preoccupation with location has taken
second place to their concern about security of income.
The turnaround in sentiment has been particularly apparent in the London
office market, which was long spurned by investors who were dismayed by the
large oversupply of buildings and the weakness of tenant demand.
This upturn in demand, which was led by overseas investors, particularly
from Germany, has been particularly apparent in the market for highly
over-rented offices - where there is little prospect of any rental increases
in the foreseeable future, because the rent payable exceeds the market rate.
The attraction of the building's high, secure yield outweighed the poor
prospects for rental growth.
The state of the office rental market shows less promise than the investment
market. The twin problems faced by the industry - oversupply of buildings
and weak demand - are still forcing rents downwards in most regions.
There are sharp variations between different parts of the country. The
over-supply of offices is most pronounced in London which, as a result, has
suffered the sharpest decline in rents.
A recent report by Chesterton, chartered surveyors, found that nearly 18m sq
ft of new or refurbished space was available to let in city centres around
the country, of which 15m sq ft is in London.
Outside London, office rents have tended to fall more as a result of weak
demand than sharp over-supply. Vacancy rates have remained much lower than
in London, because there was much less speculative development. Chesterton,
chartered surveyors, estimated that the London vacancy rate was about 18 per
cent, compared with a rate of about 12 per cent in regional centres.
As a result, rents have not tumbled to the same extent as in London. Whereas
in London's west end rents have fallen by 62 per cent from their peak, in
the north-west rents have fallen by 9 per cent, while in the East Midlands
they have fallen by 14 per cent.
These large variations in demand and supply between different UK cities
result in marked differences in the prognosis for rental recovery in
different parts of the country. On average, growth is expected to return in
1995 or 1996. However, cities with a relatively tight supply of office
buildings, such as Birmingham, Manchester, Leeds, Glasgow and Edinburgh, may
see rental growth before 1995.
The factors governing rental prospects are complex. First, much depends on
how fast tenants respond to an improvement in the economy. Many will delay
expanding into new offices, because they already have plenty of unused space
in their existing offices.
Second, the difficulties of reletting old offices mean that many tenants who
wish to move to new premises are unable to dispose of their old leases.
Third, the over-supply figures may prove to be exaggerated, because much of
the empty office stock is virtually unusable. There is already a two-tier
market: the new or good-quality second-hand accommodation attracts far more
lettings than the poorer-quality space, where availability rates remain
stubbornly high.
The difficulties in securing lettings of low-grade offices may lead to these
premises being taken off the market. Office owners have an incentive to
decommission buildings, because it removes their liability to pay rates.
This possibility that older offices will never find a tenant raises yet
another uncertainty. At what stage will property owners be prepared to
resume development?
In general, market rental values are too low to justify development on a
speculative basis. Moreover, banks are unwilling to lend on a speculative
basis, so the only developers capable of undertaking projects are those with
their own resources or institutional backing.
However, there has been an upturn in the number of schemes winning finance,
because they have secured pre-lets. Tenants with leases that expire in
several years time would often prefer to take advantage of low land and
construction costs by agreeing to lease a building now than wait until their
leases expire when the supply of suitable offices may have greatly
diminished.
Even the speculative developer is making a come-back. Pearl Assurance and
Arcona Properties are developing a 30,000 sq ft speculative office scheme in
London's West end. Mr Dieter Bock, the German financier at the helm of
Lonhro, and Lord Palumbo, chairman of the Arts Council, have announced
proposals for developing Number One Poultry, on a speculative basis. Great
Portland Estates recently announces its intention to start development on a
80,000 sq ft building in Great Portland Street.
These first stirrings in the development market do not yet signal a
full-blown revival in the property market. Nonetheless, they are a sign that
the first building blocks for recovery are firmly in place.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6552 Subdividers and Developers, Ex Cemeteries.
    P1541 Industrial Buildings and Warehouses.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT934-7365</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DKSDHAH8FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931119
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / Survey of UK Property (2): Optimism strengthens in spite of
downbeat statistics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AFTER THREE years of decline, the investment market for top-quality property
is beginning to strengthen. The fall in interest rates, following sterling's
exit from the exchange rate mechanism in September 1992, helped stabilise
the market. It reduced the risk of tenant failures and eased the pressure on
company balance sheets, lessening the need to sell property.
Moreover, the falling cost of finance and the diminished returns on cash
helped attract overseas buyers and private investors into the market. By
late spring, the growing confidence had prompted institutional investors to
return.
Potential demand for property is widely considered to be at its highest for
at least five years. Property companies raised about Pounds 1.5bn in new
funds in the first half of 1993, and are channelling much of this into the
market. Overseas investors are also making significant investments; their
1992 total is expected to be around Pounds 1 1/2 -Pounds 2bn. But these
sources of finance are overshadowed by the potential demand from UK
institutions, which are prepared to invest Pounds 7bn in commercial property
over the next 12-18 months, according to DTZ Debenham Thorpe, property
advisers.
Last year, the combined institutional net purchases of just less than Pounds
1bn was half the 1991 total, and one of the lowest recorded over the past 12
years. As a percentage of new investment, property slipped from about 15 per
cent at the start of the 1980s to 5 per cent at the start of 1993.
But there has been a sea change in attitude in the past few months. Like the
mid-1970s, when institutions returned in force, there is a widespread view
that the property cycle is on an upswing. Admittedly, this view is not
wholly reinforced by official statistics. Figures from the Central
Statistical Office suggest institutions were actually net sellers of UK
property during the second quarter of 1993. Nonetheless, most commentators
believe these statistics give a misleadingly downbeat impression. The large
number of transactions agreed in the second quarter are unlikely to show up
in the figures until later in the year.
The speed of the revival in investor interest is even prompting fears of
overheating in some parts of the market. Competition is intense for
buildings with blue-chip tenants and long leases. Security of income has
become one of property's main attractions. Falling bond yields highlight the
yields available from property - which rose above gilt yields in 1992 for
the first time since the 1960s.
Some investors fear such attractions could be eroded by legislative changes.
The government has announced plans to abolish privity of contract - whereby
the original tenant retains the ultimate responsibility for paying rent
throughout the lease - on new leases.
The impact this will have is hotly debated. Around 60 per cent of the UK's
50 largest funds surveyed by DTZ Debenham Thorpe believed the new
legislation, if not applied retrospectively, would have no impact on the
value of their existing portfolios. A quarter, however, feared it would
reduce the value of their existing assets.
The DTZ survey also found that nine out of 10 respondents believe there will
be a recovery in values over the next couple of years. At present, however,
investor demand is largely restricted to a narrow band of top-quality
property. Property with shorter leases and less financially secure tenants
is still difficult to sell, not least because banks remain highly cautious
about lending.
But the banks' caution is not necessarily a cause for dismay. It may lead to
a shortage of development finance, which will restrict the supply of new
property and encourage a revival in rental values.
</TEXT>
<XX>
