<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / UK Company News: Merchant Retail falls into the red
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Difficult trading conditions and losses on disposal of businesses left
Merchant Retail Group with pre-tax losses of Pounds 31,000 for the half year
to September 25, against profits of Pounds 467,000.
The company said trading was particularly difficult at Normans, the
supermarket chain in the south-west of England.
Despite good performances by the two recent openings, sales declined by 1
per cent and margins remained under pressure.
Sales at Joplings, the north-east of England department store chain, were up
3 per cent and margins had firmed slightly.
The Perfume Shop, where the number of branches had doubled to 18, showed
losses of Pounds 202,000 which was lower than budgeted. However, the
expansion was making the group more dependent on second half trading.
There were losses of Pounds 223,000 on the sale of Barnums and Town and
Country Manner.
The shares fell 3p to close at 12p.
Turnover was Pounds 80.3m (Pounds 81.2m) for operating profits of Pounds
1.08m (Pounds 1.31m). Interest charges were lower at Pounds 887,000 (Pounds
1.2m).
Losses per share were 0.15p (earnings 0.44p). The interim dividend is cut to
0.2p (0.35p).
