<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / Storehouse surprises City with rebound to Pounds 11.6m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STOREHOUSE, the retail group comprising BHS, Mothercare and Blazer, shrugged
off City fears that its recovery might be faltering as it unveiled interim
pre-tax profits of Pounds 11.6m compared with a Pounds 27.3m loss.
Both figures were distorted by exceptional items. Last year's was hit by a
Pounds 30.4m charge to cover losses on the sale of the Habitat and Richards
chains and this year's was depressed by a Pounds 6.4m provision from the
sale of the US Mothercare business.
Stripping out exceptionals, profits rose almost six-fold from Pounds 3.1m to
Pounds 18m.
The shares, which had fallen after rival group Burton announced
disappointing results last week, recovered 17p to 200p.
Sales in continuing businesses were up 5 per cent in the 28 weeks to October
9, with operating profits up 45 per cent. Storehouse expected a
'significant' increase in year-end profits.
But it warned consumer confidence remained 'delicate and easily disturbed'.
Mr Keith Edelman, chief executive, said: 'We are very concerned about the
possibility of VAT on children's clothing, which accounts for a quarter of
turnover.'
Gross margins have also fallen slightly, with the margin at BHS down almost
one percentage point as a result of a price promotion, and Mothercare's
margin down about one point after a repositioning on price.
Total group turnover fell from Pounds 617.4m to Pounds 484.9m, as last
year's figures included sales from Habitat and Richards.
Sales at BHS increased from Pounds 323.4m to Pounds 337.2m, and operating
profits from Pounds 10.5m to Pounds 15.4m. Mr Edelman said BHS was
under-represented in many parts of the country and would step up its opening
programme.
Sales at Mothercare increased 6 per cent to Pounds 140.9m, with profits at
Pounds 2.1m, from Pounds 1.7m. Sales improved 6 per cent at Blazer, with
losses down slightly. Mr Edelman said One-Up, the discount format which has
replaced some of BHS's poorly-performing stores, had traded satisfactorily
in its first three months.
The interim dividend was unchanged at 2.5p, with earnings up to 1.4p,
against a 6.9p loss, after exceptionals. Mr Edelman hinted at a possible
dividend rise next year.
Lex, Page 26
London SE, Page 48
People, Page 22
</TEXT>
