<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / Experts top up their pensions in time for the Budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ON THE principle of following what the experts do and not what they say,
people should get their pension contributions up to date before the Budget
speech at the end of this month.
In anticipation of what they believe the chancellor will announce on
November 30, leading tax practitioners are accelerating pension payments -
and even taking out loans to do so.
Partners at the UK's largest accountancy firms, including Coopers &amp; Lybrand
and KPMG Peat Marwick, are being urged to top up their pensions before the
Budget statement. Price Waterhouse is considering similar action. Their
action reflects concern that the government has decided to remove tax relief
on pensions.
Mr Peter Wyman, a tax partner with Coopers &amp; Lybrand, said: 'We are
suggesting to partners that they think very seriously about getting up to
date before the Budget.'
The chancellor may remove upper-rate tax relief on pension contributions or
eliminate tax-free lump sums when a pension matures. A third and more likely
option - which would have a less immediately visible impact - would be to
impose capital gains tax or remove advance corporation tax relief on pension
funds.
As self-employed taxpayers, many partners in professional firms would
normally not pay their contributions for the last tax year until next April,
but may now try to pay both last year's and this year's before the end of
this month.
Mr Ian Barlow, a tax partner with KPMG Peat Marwick, said yesterday: 'We are
certainly taking precautions.' He had urged corporate clients to do the
same.
The gamble is that if the chancellor does not remove tax concessions but
instead raises the rate of income tax, they will not be able to claim the
additional tax reliefs generated at this higher level of tax.
But Mr Wyman said that this option was unlikely, and that the additional
interest on accelerated contributions would in any case partially partly
compensate.
Call to limit state pensions, Page 13
</TEXT>
