<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / Number of strikes falls to record low
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE POOR international image of Britain as a strike-prone country is waning.
The latest labour dispute figures of the Department of Employment suggest
that Britain has nearly attained the low levels of industrial conflict
enjoyed by Switzerland and Sweden.
The latest provisional total of strikes released yesterday by the government
reveal that only 16 strikes took place in September, the lowest number since
such statistics began a century ago.
In the 12 months to this September, 188 disputes took place. Only 8,000
working days were lost in September as a result of strikes, the smallest
total recorded in official statistics since December 1937.
As many as 622,000 working days were lost due to strikes up to last
September. That is more than the 526,000 lost working days recorded for the
same period to September last year, but it represents the second smallest
figure since official figures began in 1893.
The cumulative total of workers involved in disputes which began during the
12 months to this September was 241,000, with only 3,000 in September alone.
The 12-month figure is higher than the 154,000 recorded for the previous
period to September 1992 but still represents the second lowest figure since
1934.
The latest comparative strike statistics for last year, published by the
Geneva-based International Labour Organisation, suggest that Britain lost
far fewer working days from strikes in 1992 than Germany, France and Italy,
its main European competitors. Only paradigms of industrial harmony such as
Sweden and Switzerland recorded much lower figures for lost working days.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8631 Labor Organizations.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
