<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / Average earnings growth down to 3% in September
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNDERLYING growth in average earnings fell to a historic low of 3 per cent
in September, Department of Employment figures showed yesterday.
The government's figures follow reports from independent research
organisations, including Incomes Data Services, that basic pay settlements
have bottomed out and may be set to increase again.
However, the official figures cover more than basic pay settlements. For
example, they include overtime payments, which after a slight increase in
July fell back in August and September.
The government figures show that underlying average earnings growth for the
12 months to the end of September fell to 3 per cent from 3.25 per cent in
August.
Separate sector rates were 2.5 per cent for services (from 2.75 per cent on
August), 4.5 per cent in production industries and 4.5 per cent in
manufacturing. The latter two were stable.
There are two main influences on this fall in earnings growth, which is at
its lowest since a temporary incomes policy in the late 1960s.
First, the public-sector pay ceiling set at 1.5 per cent by Mr Norman
Lamont, the former chancellor, is depressing average pay settlements and
reducing the overall service sector average. Workers covered by the ceiling
make up about one quarter of the sector.
The second factor was that manufacturing output faltered in the third
quarter of 1993, resulting in a decrease in overtime working in
manufacturing.
Manufacturing output per head in September grew by 4.9 per cent in the three
months to September compared with the same three months a year earlier, down
from 5.2 per cent in the three months to August.
Unit wage costs dropped 0.6 per cent over the same period, a lower fall than
in the three months to August, when they fell 0.8 per cent.
