<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / Rolls-Royce to shed 1,000 more jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ROLLS-ROYCE, the aero-engine and industrial power group, is to shed an
additional 1,000 jobs in its UK aerospace operations next year because of
continuing difficult trading conditions in its civil and defence aero-engine
businesses.
The latest restructuring, confirmed yesterday by the company, will increase
the total of job cuts in its aerospace activities to 3,000 next year on top
of the 3,000 jobs it is losing this year.
The company announced last year that it planned to shed 5,000 jobs in 1993
and 1994 in the face of the prolonged recession in the civil aerospace
market and the post-cold war downturn in the defence sector.
It said the need to make additional reductions at its aero-engine plants in
Derby, Bristol, Sunderland, East Kilbride and Hillingdon, near Glasgow,
followed a continuing review of requirements.
The company has not ruled out compulsory redundancies.
Although Rolls-Royce this week announced new civil aero-engine orders worth
about Pounds 150m, it said overall conditions in the civil aircraft market
were not improving.
It added that the Pounds 230m provisions it made in its 1992 accounts to
cover the two-year 1993-94 restructuring programme would also cover the
additional 1,000 job cuts next year.
In total, the company will now see its aerospace workforce reduced from
29,000 people at the end of last year to 23,000 by the end of next year.
The additional cuts are expected to involve about 350 jobs at Bristol, where
the company's military engine business is concentrated, about 140 jobs at
Derby, the centre for civil engines, with the rest spread around the
company's other UK plants.
The UK group is facing intense commercial pressures from its two bigger US
competitors, General Electric and Pratt &amp; Whitney, which have also been
engaged in heavy restructuring.
All three big aero-engine makers are fighting to win new business in a
diminishing market depressed by airline losses, overcapacity and defence
spending cuts.
Rolls-Royce, whose aero-engine activities mustered a profit of only Pounds
5m on aero-engine sales of Pounds 1.078bn in the first half of this year, is
also facing heavy research and development spending on its new generation of
high-thrust Trent engines. These are to power the new large wide-body
aircraft being developed by Boeing of the US and the European Airbus
consortium.
Sir Ralph Robins, Rolls-Royce chairman, recently said he did not expect to
see any recovery in the civil aircraft market before 1995 or 1996.
</TEXT>
