<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / Hurd touts European credentials
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR DOUGLAS HURD, the foreign secretary, will today outline the government's
'wholehearted' commitment to the European Union in a move designed to
outline the party's pro-European credentials.
In a speech to the Sheffield Chamber of Commerce tonight, Mr Hurd will
attempt to set a new pro-European agenda and implicitly urge Euro-sceptics
to accept that the party's damaging battle over Maastricht is over.
A draft of his speech says: 'We have no doubts about our place at the heart
of Europe. The United Kingdom decided on its European destiny almost a
generation ago. There is no need to fight that battle over again. Nor do we
need to re-enact the battle of Maastricht.'
Mr Hurd's speech follows remarks by three key economic ministers at this
week's Confederation of British Industry conference in Harrogate, at which
they attempted to regain ground lost to the right at the party conference.
The left of the party were dismayed by speeches by ministers such as Mr
Peter Lilley, the social security secretary, which had drawn applause for
attacks on the European Commission.
Mr Hurd is determined that the party should unite round a policy that is
'wholeheartedly committed to the European Union' but which is not afraid to
argue Britain's interests within the Community.
He will tell his audience that the battle to convince Britain's European
partners that economic problems will not be solved by increasing regulatory
burdens on businesses will continue.
But the draft goes on: 'The fact that we argue with our partners in Europe,
that we disagree with them on many things, most obviously about the
prospects for early movement towards monetary union, does not mean that
Europe is irretrievably divided. The days of a divided Europe are over.'
The foreign secretary will also argue for an enlarged Europe expanding to
the north and east which is in tune with business opinion and public
opinion. And he will claim that the government 'is second to none' in its
idealism on Europe.
Meanwhile, Mr Geoffrey Martin, head of the European Commission's UK offices,
has warned of a 'democratic deficit' in Westminster about the UK's future in
Europe. He defined the 'deficit' as a 'lack of transparency and
accountability' and a gap between what people needed and what was negotiated
on their behalf.
He said at Hull University that unless MPs recognised their
responsibilities, 'the dangerous democratic deficit about Europe will
continue to exist'.
</TEXT>
