<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / Prison officers' dispute curbed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL HOWARD, the home secretary, yesterday won a High Court injunction
preventing the Prison Officers' Association from stepping up its industrial
action next week.
The association had threatened to stop accepting most admissions to prisons
for three days starting on Monday - a move the Prison Service management had
warned would represent a serious threat to law and order.
A High Court judge, Mr Justice May, yesterday accepted the government's
arguments that, because prison officers hold the office of constables, they
are not protected under employment law if they take industrial action that
breaches their contracts.
However, the judge agreed with lawyers for the association that the logical
consequences of his ruling meant the association could no longer effectively
act as a trade union.
He added that it was 'remarkable' that it had been treated as a union for so
long without the issue of its protection under employment law being
challenged.
Mr John Bartell, the association's chairman, said the union was certain to
appeal against the injunction and would continue the legal fight as long as
necessary.
He said: 'The home secretary now has a major problem on his hands. This
ruling is only part of a long legal process.
'In the long run, the courts will vindicate the fact that we are a trade
union. I do not believe the public will allow this shabby recourse to the
courts to create another GCHQ.'
The association's national executive was last night meeting to discuss its
next move.
Mr Derek Lewis, director-general of the prison service, welcomed the
injunction. He denied it had been sought as a back-door means of breaking
the association, saying the management wished to have constructive relations
with prison staff.
The injunction had been sought 'with the greatest of reluctance' and only
because of the seriousness of the action threatened.
Had the action gone ahead, an extra 1,700 prisoners would have had to be
accommodated in police cells by next Wednesday.
A ballot of the association's membership last month approved action short of
an all-out strike to protest against the government's market-testing
proposals. It has already begun limited action in the form of a
work-to-rule.
</TEXT>
