<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / Strike shipyard may lay off 750
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
YARROW Shipbuilders on Clydeside proposes to lay off half of its 1,500
manual workers from Monday and cut back production in the face of an
official strike by the company's 600 white collar staff which has lasted 10
days.
Staff belonging to the MSF general technical union are demanding pay rises
equal to the 3.7 per cent plus Pounds 300 deal secured by manual workers at
the yard in February after a bitter dispute.
The company has withdrawn a 'final' offer to the staff of a basic 1.8 per
cent wage rise plus a further award of up to 2.6 per cent based on the
introduction of a performance-related pay scheme.
Talks were going on last night over the lay offs, but the two sides were not
in pay negotiations.
Yarrow said it would try to keep the shipyard open through rotation of its
manual workers, but pointed out that the skilled supervisors were on strike
and only 30 managers were available to do their work.
The yard is building three Type 23 frigates for the Royal Navy and two
frigates for Malaysia.
Ms Jane Lindsay, one of the white collar staff strike leaders, called
yesterday for a return to the negotiating table. 'We have been negotiating
with the company for the past two-and-a-half years and management has
offered nothing new,' she said.
'All we want is equal treatment with the manual workers.
'Surely it is not too much to expect a little bit of social justice for the
workforce so we can carry on with the business of building ships and getting
more orders for the yard?'
Union officials said they would like Acas, the conciliation service, to
intervene, accusing Yarrow senior management of being too abrasive.
</TEXT>
