<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / Miners' consortium in jeopardy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FUTURE of Monktonhall Mineworkers, the consortium of miners who lease a
British Coal pit near Edinburgh, was uncertain last night after the miners
decisively rejected a takeover offer from RJB Mining, the quoted
Nottinghamshire mining company.
Monktonhall also dismissed Quayle Munro, the Edinburgh-based merchant bank
which was the consortium's financial adviser. There were indications that
the consortium was holding talks with another, unnamed, investor.
RJB Mining had offered the 167 miners Pounds 1,000 each for their shares,
for which each had paid Pounds 10,000. Quayle Munro had warned the miners
that if they refused the offer, and in the absence of a rival bid, the
company would be likely to go into liquidation.
Monktonhall has net liabilities of Pounds 2m and lost Pounds 3.7m in the
year ended May 1993.
Although RJB Mining was approached by Quayle Munro for Monktonhall, and its
offer was recommended by the consortium's board, it was seen by many of the
miners as a hostile takeover. RJB, which had been guaranteeing the workers'
wages since September, insisted on 90 per cent acceptance. RJB said last
night it would not extend the offer. The number of acceptances was not
revealed.
The rejection means the mine will not get the Pounds 3m investment RJB had
offered, while an offer of finance from the Department of Trade and Industry
could also lapse. But Lothian regional council said last night its own
package of assistance would be available 'to support any credible proposals
that are acceptable to the men'.
Mr Ian Jones, Quayle Munro's chief executive, said there had not been 'the
necessary close liaison with the directors of Monktonhall and ourselves'.
</TEXT>
