<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / Graphology 'a waste of money'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN MCGOOKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES which use handwriting analysis as part of their recruitment
process are wasting their money, a leading psychologist claimed yesterday.
Dr Donald McLeod, a corporate psychologist with the Independent Assessment
and Research Centre at Ashridge Management College, said: 'If you're using
graphology as an indicator of people's effectiveness in the workplace, you
might as well throw a sheaf of application forms out the window and choose
those that land face up.'
In a report for the British Psychological Society, Dr McLeod - previously
chief psychologist for the Civil Service Commission - points to recent
research which he says indicates that a full-scale psychometric test is the
most effective way of studying a potential employee's suitability.
Graphology is firmly at the bottom, producing 'zero predictive
effectiveness', Dr McLeod said.
But the report was attacked as 'alarming' by Ms Mary Nicholson, head of the
London-based Graphology Business, which provides a handwriting consultancy
service to corporate clients.
'Graphology is based on a very precise theory, with practitioners needing to
use their psychological knowledge to be able to understand very precise
signs,' she said.
While the use of handwriting analysis is not widespread in the UK - in some
US states it is prohibited for recruitment purposes - some notable employers
do use graphology tests. For example, all applicants to merchant bank SG
Warburg must submit handwriting samples for anal-ysis.
The bank stresses it takes the results seriously, but says the handwriting
test comes towards the end of a lengthy selection procedure and that a
candidate would not be rejected solely on the basis of it.
Analysis in recruitment seems to be accorded more credibility in France, but
may be less significant than in recent years.
For example, Rhone-Poulenc, the chemicals company, says that while it once
used handwriting analysis to sift application forms in the first instance,
it now only refers to a graphologist where there might be a doubt about a
candidate, and even then the candidate would be called back for a further
interview.
'We never make a decision based on a graphologist's comments,' says the
company's human resources department, calling the analysis 'a tool' used to
contribute to the overall picture of a candid-ate.
French headhunters would tend to use a graphologist's services, but other
testing methods are also employed.
The Validity of Graphology in Personnel Assessment, British Psychological
Society, St Andrews House, 48 Princess Road East, Leicester LE1 7DR. Free.
</TEXT>
