<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / The Queen's Speech: DTI given powers to abolish 'red tape' -
De-regulation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, ROLAND RUDD and RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR said yesterday the government would 'sweep away red tape' by
repealing legislation in the biggest package of de-regulation since the
fifties.
The de-regulation bill will give sweeping powers to the Department of Trade
and Industry to abolish hundreds of regulations without having to refer to
parliament.
Labour yesterday criticised the government for trying to extend the power of
the executive by seeking to repeal existing instruments without specifying
in advance the legislation covered.
It also fears that the government will try to use a so-called Henry VIII
clause - allowing ministers to repeal primary legislation by order. The
clause gets its name by providing dictatorial powers similar to those of the
Tudor king.
Charter 88, the constitutional pressure group, said contemplation of the
Henry VIII clause 'heralded an elective tyranny' and warned of a new
authoritarianism in government.
Mr Stephen Alembritis of the Federation of Small Businesses said the
far-reaching powers were the key to giving momentum to the de-regulation
process.
He said: 'The de-regulation bill has been a long time coming, but its
inclusion in the speech reflects the priority the prime minister has given
to the initiative.'
Consumer organisations warned, however, that cutting red tape could sweep
away laws which protect health and safety, enforce standards across
industries and provide essential information for consumers.
'If ministers can do things virtually by decree,' said Mr Phillip Cullum of
the Consumers' Association, 'there will be a temptation to act without
consulting all interested parties.'
Mr Peter Morgan, director-general of the Institute of Directors, urged the
government to ensure that its de-regulation initiative continued beyond the
bill by taking other steps such as simplifying the valued added tax system
and strengthening the machinery for deregulation.
'One bill cannot put right the accumulated mistakes of decades and even
centuries of legislation,' he warned. He also called for abolition of the
statutory audit requirement for small firms.
Mr John Edmonds, general secretary of the GMB general union, told union
members in Newcastle yesterday: 'Safety laws and regulations are not red
tape or burdens on business, they are the hallmark of civilisation and
contribute to high quality businesses.'
Seven business task forces are reviewing all regulations in everything from
health and safety rules, which label some common household products as
dangerous substances, to the regulations setting standards for outside
recreation.
Mr Neil Hamilton, corporate affairs minister, said the bill would lead to an
accumulation of changes and a significant cost reduction to business.
The bill will also include measures to remove obstacles to market-testing of
civil service work and contracting out in local government. These will make
it easier for ministers and local authorities to delegate powers to
contractors where that is barred by legislation.
</TEXT>
