<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / The Queen's Speech: MPs will scrutinise MI5 and GCHQ -
Secret services
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government is taking another step towards more open government by
submitting the intelligence services for the first time to parliamentary
scrutiny.
According to Foreign Office officials, the Intelligence Services Bill
announced in the speech yesterday is still being fine-tuned before its
expected introduction in the House of Lords later this month. But there is
now agreement that it should contain a provision for a parliamentary
committee responsible for oversight and accountability of MI5, the Secret
Intelligence Service, M16, and GCHQ, the government's intelligence-gathering
communications centre.
Parliamentary scrutiny is widely viewed as the most controversial aspect of
the new bill. It also places the SIS and GCHQ on a statutory footing - as
M15 was in the Security Service Act 1989.
The bill will enable all three intelligence services to be investigated by
complaints tribunals outside parliament.
But the government has decided to test parliamentary opinion as to whether
it should go further in meeting the recommendation of the Commons home
affairs committee last year that it should be entrusted with scrutinising
the activities of all three intelligence services.
The government had earlier aired the suggestion that the supervising
committee - whether extra-parliamentary or parliamentary - should be made up
of privy councillors.
However, MPs have argued that the inclusion of privy councillors who have
sworn allegiance to the crown would dilute the critical function of the
committee and turn it into a creature of government.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, is also understood to be facing pressure
from within his own party and intelligence officers who believe that the
open-government policy may already have gone too far.
Sir Ivan Lawrence, Tory chairman of last session's Commons home affairs
committee, said last night: 'I was against opening up the intelligence
services in the first place . . . I think you have more to lose than to gain
by it.'
The intelligence services fear that the government's policy of bringing them
increasingly into the public eye risks compromising the security of
individuals.
Over the past year, the names of all three heads of the intelligence
agencies have been published by the government, and the head of M15, Mrs
Stella Rimmington, has allowed herself to be photographed. It emerged last
night that one of the main speakers in the Lords on the Intelligence
Services Bill will be Baroness Park, who retired from a senior SIS post in
1980.
</TEXT>
