<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / The Queen's Speech: Mines sell-off bill may come within
weeks - British Coal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is expected to publish a bill to privatise British Coal
within weeks as ministers press ahead with controversial plans to sell off
the industry by early 1995.
The legislation to enact what Lord Parkinson, former energy secretary,
described as the ultimate privatisation, comes as British Coal presses ahead
with a programme of closures expected to shut more than half of its
remaining 30 pits.
The legislation, which could come as early as next week, will attempt to
resolve the contentious issues of pensions and concessionary coal for
employees. The Labour party and pit unions are likely to concentrate on both
subjects in their campaign to keep British Coal in the public sector.
Potential buyers will have to wait some months, possibly until the middle of
next year, before the government decides which pits are for sale and at what
price. Ministers have already announced that British Coal is to be split
into five parts for privatisation. The composition of the areas, to be
grouped around Scotland, north-east England, Yorkshire, Nottinghamshire and
Wales has yet to be determined.
There is uncertainty about which pits will be closed before privatisation.
British Coal has indicated to unions a cut in the number of deep-mine pits
to 23, but a further reduction to at most 15 is likely before privatisation.
The long-term market is unlikely to sustain more than 12 deep mines.
Last year British Coal sold 65m tonnes of coal to the England and Wales
generators, but by the late 1990s the total annual market for power station
coal is likely to fall to about 30m tonnes.
The privatisation should also pave the way for privatisation of British Coal
subsidiaries including Coal Products, which sells smokeless fuels, British
Fuels, the retail distribution arm, Compower, the computer services company,
and the Coal Research Establishment.
Unions are opposed in principle to privatisation, but the Union of
Democratic Mineworkers is part of a consortium which is considering bids and
British Association of Colliery Management is looking at the possibility of
management buy-outs. The government is offering financial help for employee
teams interested in buying pits.
Mr John Monks, TUC general secretary, said: 'History will charge this
government with the murder of the British coal mining industry. Now, in the
ultimate insult, they are seeking to sell off the dismembered body.'
</TEXT>
