<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / World Trade News: Warning tempers welcome from Tokyo - Japan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN yesterday welcomed the US vote for the North American Free Trade
Agreement, but warned that it will watch closely to ensure there is no
discrimination against countries outside the region.
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, who himself won parliamentary passage of
important plans for political reform only hours after the US vote, praised
the US govern JAPAN ment for getting Nafta through the House of
Representatives.
Nafta will avert protectionist moves in the US Congress, predicted Mr
Terusuke Terada, foreign ministry spokesman. However, Nafta should be
implemented in accordance with Gatt rules and must not raise obstacles to
foreign countries, he added.
The foreign ministry's warning was echoed by the Keidanren business
federation. Mr Gaishi Hiraiwa, its chairman, said the Keidanren would
closely monitor the fair enforcement of rules of origin under Nafta.
Separately, banking officials predicted that the accord could encourage more
Japanese companies and banks to invest in Mexico.
Shares in Tokyo rose sharply just before the Nafta vote, partly in
anticipation of success, but the Nikkei 225 average fell back later in the
day, to end up 57.61 points at 18,166.32.
</TEXT>
