<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 93 / Bosnians agree safe passage for aid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LEADERS of the three warring factions in Bosnia yesterday promised to end
interference with United Nations humanitarian aid supplies on which over 3m
people depend for survival.
They signed a 'joint and solemn commitment' to allow safe passage for UN
convoys, after Mrs Sadako Ogata, UN High Commissioner for Refugees, called
them to Geneva in what was described as a 'last ditch' effort to unblock the
UN aid effort in Bosnia.
This has been increasingly paralysed by fierce fighting between Bosnian
Croats and mainly Moslem government forces in central Bosnia, and by
deliberate attempts on the part of all sides to hinder supplies getting
through, including attacks on UN workers. The UNHCR has also been concerned
at the refusal of local militias to let through clothes, fuel and shelter
materials.
The accord calls for a suspension of hostilities along aid supply routes
when convoys are passing, free and unconditional access to the best routes,
safety for UN and other humanitarian workers, the right of the UN and the
International Committee of the Red Cross to decide what supplies should go
to whom, and respect for international humanitarian law.
At a news conference afterwards, Mrs Ogata described the accord as 'the
minimum' required to avert disaster this winter, but added that without
peace 'I don't know whether a humanitarian catastrophe can be avoided'.
Mindful of the many broken promises in the past, she earlier told the
meeting she was 'not asking for new promises, but for deeds'.
The accord was signed by Mr Haris Silajdzic, the Bosnian prime minister, Mr
Radovan Karadzic, the Bosnian Serb leader, and Mr Mate Boban, for the
Bosnian Croats, who were accompanied by senior military commanders. The high
commissioner said that, significantly, it was the first time all three
parties had signed a joint assurance on security for aid deliveries.
Mrs Ogata said she would immediately recommend a resumption of UN aid
convoys into central Bosnia, suspended nearly four weeks ago after a Danish
driver was killed and nine other UN personnel wounded in what seems to have
been a deliberate attack by Bosnian Moslem forces.
In a toughly worded opening address to the meeting, which was also attended
by the head of the ICRC, Mrs Ogata told the Bosnian leaders that they alone
bore the responsibility for the suffering in their country.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>BAZ  Bosnia-Hercegovina, East Europe.
</CN>
